[1]
Date: Fri 5 Oct 2007
Source: DEFRA news release, ref 349/07 [edited]
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2007/071005a.htm>

Defra update on foot-and-mouth disease situation
------------------------------------------------
Defra has today [5 Oct 2007] published a further report on ongoing
epidemiological work into the foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) outbreak
[see item 2].
At day 63 of the FMD outbreak there are currently 8 confirmed
Infected Premises. Evidence continues to indicate that this outbreak
is likely to be confined to a relatively small area of the country
and not become geographically extensive and that the risk of spread
outside of the FMD risk area remains very low.
Fred Landeg, deputy chief veterinary officer said, "The cases since
21 Sep 2007 have all been within the existing Protection Zone. Our
detailed investigations indicate that they all derived from other
infected premises within the zone. That is why we again stepped up
our surveillance.
"We took the decision to cull 4 Dangerous Contacts for Infected
Premises 8. Final laboratory tests are awaited but the initial
results are negative, which provides reassurance that disease has not
spread from the last infected premises (IP8).
"The evidence indicates that spread is local. While the exact
mechanism cannot be firmly established, it is most likely to be
windborne or mechanical transmission.
"It remains the case that the outbreak is most likely to be confined
to this small area in the south east of England, but our intensive
surveillance work continues. That does not mean that we can become
complacent about FMD in the rest of the country. Animal keepers must
continue to be vigilant in checking stock."
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[For the above-mentioned Defra FMD 2007 Epidemiology Report, which
unfortunately does not allow copying, subscribers are referred to
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/footandmouth/pdf/epidreport300907.pdf>.
The report (17 pages) includes a correction to the descriptive
epidemiology of IP4 (regarding its notice and reporting by the
owner), and separate epidemiological descriptions of IP6, IP7, and
IP8. The epidemiology of IP5 is still under investigation.
The report includes additional epidemiological data, a review of
potential for future cases or spread of FMD in the UK, and detailed,
useful maps. The previous epidemiological report covered the events
until 21 Sep 2007. - Mod.AS]
