[2]
Date: Fri 5 Oct 2007
Source: BBC News [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/1/hi/uk/7030248.stm>

The latest outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease is unlikely to spread
outside Surrey, government vets have said.
Defra said epidemiological studies of the latest cases confirmed the
belief that the disease is unlikely to spread outside the area.
Evidence suggested that in the newest cases, the disease was
transmitted by the wind or carried by machinery, the report said.
Deputy chief vet Fred Landeg said, "We hope that we will not discover
any further new cases." The report showed that the latest outbreak
was "most likely to remain small and not become geographically
extensive," he added.
Dr Landeg also said the only potential link between Pirbright -- the
source of the 1st outbreak in August [2007] -- and the secondary
outbreak in September [2007] was through human or vehicle movement.
It will be at least 30 days from the last confirmed case, discovered
last weekend [29-30 Sep 2007], before the surveillance zone in Surrey
can be lifted, he said.
--
